> IIUC they are still called through std::addressof when the type has an user-defined address operator

The entire purpose of `std::addressof` is to get the address of an object regardless of whether it defines an address operator. It can be portably implemented as:

``` c++
// Add T's cv-qualifiers to U
template <class T, class U>
struct __xref { using type = U; };
template <class T, class U>
struct __xref<const T> { using type = const U; };
template <class T, class U>
struct __xref<volatile T> { using type = volatile U; };
template <class T, class U>
struct __xref<const volatile T> { using type = const volatile U; };

template <class T>
T* addressof(T& t) noexcept {
  return static_cast<T*>(static_cast<__xref<T,void>*>(
    &reinterpret_cast<__xref<T,char>&>(t)));
}
```

If you _want_ to call user-defined address operators, you use `&` instead of `addressof`.

> The way it is right now, if variant is made constexpr, and it store types with a constexpr addressof operator, constexpr get wouldn't work because it would attempt to use `std::addressof`.

Whose variant? range-v3's? My (somewhat sloppy and rushed) variant is as constexpr as I believe is possible - heck, I have constexpr variadic perfect-forwarding `visit` - and nowhere in the implementation does it take the address of an element with either `&` or `addressof`.

WIP solution modifies the requires clauses to use parameters of type "reference to function returning `T`":

``` c++
requires (T (&t)(), U (&u)()) {
  // ...
  common_type_t<T, U>(t());
  common_type_t<T, U>(u());
}
```

which works as intended with `void` for `T` and `U`. (`CommonReference` also needs some occurrences of `T&` replaced by `add_lvalue_reference_t<T>`.) I'm reasonably certain this preserves the existing semantics - although it breaks the fragile iterator.cpp test of the second overload of `iter_swap2` for as yet unknown reasons.

